==Overview== The Mukaiyama Kofun is located at the end of a low hill with an elevation of 50 meters on the south bank of the Kumozu River in central Mie Prefecture. It is a "two conjoined rectangles" type tumulus ({{ill|''{{ill|zenpō-kōhō-fun|comment=doing this because of the mass replacement error that gets rid of the links like this otherwise|lt=zenpō-kōhō-fun|ja|前方後方墳|lt=Zenpō-kōhō-fun|1=Zenpō-kōhō-fun|comment=doing this because I need to differentiate it in piped links too with my new interwiki tool as not the ambiguous phrase keyhole shaped kofun|1=zenpō-kōhō-fun|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/zenpō-kōhō-fun|13=User:Immanuelle/zenpō-kōhō-fun|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}}''|前方後方墳|lt=Zenpō-kōhō-fun|1=Zenpō-kōhō-fun|comment=doing this because I need to differentiate it in piped links too with my new interwiki tool as not the ambiguous phrase keyhole shaped kofun|1=zenpō-kōhō-fun}}). It is oriented east-to-west, with the front facing east, and has a total length of 82 meters. The tumulus was constructed in two tiers, and [[fukiishi]] and fragments of clay pottery have been found scattered around the mound, but no ''[[haniwa]]''. The [[:en:Burial chamber|Burial chamber]] is located in the posterior portion and intersects the main axis of the tumulus at an angle. It was [[archaeological excavation|excavated]] by the local landlord in 1914 and was found to contain a clay coffin. [[:en:Grave goods|Grave goods]], including three [[:en:Bronze mirror|Bronze mirror]]s, iron swords and spearheads, and tubular beads and wheel stones made from jasper, were discovered. These artifacts are stored at the [[Tokyo National Museum]] and are estimated to date from the latter half of the 4th century, in the early Kofun period. The tumulus is located about 10 minutes by car from [[Ise-Nakagawa Station]] on the [[ Kintetsu Osaka Line]]. <ref name="Shiseki">{{cite book |last1=Isomura |first1=Yukio |last2=Sakai |first2=Hideya |title=(国指定史跡事典) National Historic Site Encyclopedia |date=2012 |publisher=学生社 |isbn=4311750404}}{{in lang|ja}}</ref>
The surrounding area contains a number of large ''kofun'' from the same period, including the [[Takarazuka Kofun (Mie)|Takarazuka Kofun]], which are distributed around Mount Asaka.
A portion of the tumulus collapsed in 1973 due to the removal of topsoil, and it received protection as a National Historic Site in 1975.
*Overall length: 82.2 meters *Overall height: 10 meters *Posterior rectangular portion: 40.0 meters long x 46 meters wide x 6.0 meters high *Anterior circular portion: 35.4 meters long x 36.4 meters wide x 5.6 meters high
